Introduction

The main goal of this analysis is to figure out what factors contribute to the popularity of a song from multiple variables. Songs in this data set were popular enough to be featured on the billboard top 100 songs list at different times.

We are using dataset from leonardopena/top-spotify-songs-from-20102019-by-year

Description of Columns playlistmachinery

  1. Genre - the genre of the track
  2. Year - the release year of the recording. Note that due to vagaries of releases, re-releases, re-issues and general madness, sometimes the release years are not what you’d expect.
  3. Added - the earliest date you added the track to your collection.
  4. Beats Per Minute (BPM) - The tempo of the song.
  5. Energy - The energy of a song - the higher the value, the more energtic. song
  6. Danceability - The higher the value, the easier it is to dance to this song.
  7. Loudness (dB) - The higher the value, the louder the song.
  8. Liveness - The higher the value, the more likely the song is a live recording.
  9. Valence - The higher the value, the more positive mood for the song.
  10. Length - The duration of the song.
  11. Acousticness - The higher the value the more acoustic the song is.
  12. Speechiness - The higher the value the more spoken word the song contains.
  13. Popularity - The higher the value the more popular the song is.
  14. Duration - The length of the song.

Investigating Correlation Genre/Populatiry

Now that we know some genres have higher frequency on the bill board top 100 with dance pop songs showing up 327 times, we will investigate if the genre has any impact on popularity.

We will use the Shapiro Wilk test to determine if the popularity if normally distributed If we have normal distribution, we can use the ANOVA test (Analysis of Variances) otherwise we will use the Kruskal-Wallis test

ANOVA test is used on normal distribution to check for significant differences between the means of two or more independent variables, in this case genre and pop.

Kruskal-Wallis test is a non-parametric alternative to ANOVA test used to compare the medias of those same variables.

A p-value < 0.05 on the Shapiro-Wilk test means the data is not in a normal distribution hence the Krustal-Wallis test is recommended.

The p-value from Kruskal-Wallis* is < 0.05 indicating at least one genre has significantly popularity which the specific genre comparisons can be done using Dunn’s post-hoc test which we can look at as an addition to the current scope of this analysis.

We will add a Spearman test to get a correlation value. P-value < 0.05 shows significant correlation rho>0 shows a positive correlation between the genre and popularity.

data$genre_numeric <- as.integer(factor(data$genre))

Conclusion

Factors that have an impact on the popularity or a positive correlation are danceability, loudness and genre. This analysis mainly focused on the genre which is usually more within an artist’s control.

Dance Pop was the most popular genre from 2010 through 2018 before the popularity goes down towards 2019. The sharp decline in Dance Pop songs on the bill board 100 list represents a large change in interest in the music market and we would not recommend new artists to jump into that genre.

Pop music is trending upwards and would be a good recommendation for an artist looking to jump on to a positive trend. A few of the genres with smaller frequencies on the bill boards list are also trending upwards. It would be worth while to investigate which particular artists are trending and how they are reaching their audiences to create a shift in the music market.
